WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:05.200
my name is barb oakley and i'm so happy

00:00:03.040 --> 00:00:07.200
to be able to give you some insight with

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:08.160
this video about the neuroscience of

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:10.320
learning

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:13.120
and especially how these insights can

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:15.679
inform educational policy

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:18.160
after all perhaps the best way to move

00:00:15.679 --> 00:00:21.039
teaching and learning onto the 21st

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:23.359
century is by building on the great

00:00:21.039 --> 00:00:25.760
insights that neuroscientists and

00:00:23.359 --> 00:00:27.680
cognitive psychologists are providing

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:30.240
about the brain

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.760
we should begin by getting on the same

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:34.559
page about

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.960
reviewing what happens in the brain as

00:00:34.559 --> 00:00:40.160
you're beginning to learn

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:42.320
if we focus on one of the brain's

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:44.480
fundamental building blocks

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.399
that is the neuron

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:50.000
we can understand some of the most

00:00:46.399 --> 00:00:53.280
important aspects of how we learn

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.239
a neuron has these sort of legs

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:57.680
that

00:00:54.239 --> 00:01:00.079
dangle off it they're called dendrites

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:03.039
i show three dendrites here but there

00:01:00.079 --> 00:01:05.199
are actually there can be hundreds

00:01:03.039 --> 00:01:06.960
and there are these little toes that

00:01:05.199 --> 00:01:09.439
emerge off of the

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:11.600
dendrites these toes are called

00:01:09.439 --> 00:01:13.840
dendritic spines

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:15.280
and then we have a sort of arm that

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:18.080
comes up above

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:19.600
that's called an axon

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:22.479
when you're learning

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:24.880
neurons are sending electrical signals

00:01:22.479 --> 00:01:27.680
to each other making a little web of

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:29.600
connections in long-term memory in the

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:31.200
neocortex

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:33.520
a lot of times you'll hear that you

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:35.600
don't need to memorize anything because

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:38.079
you can always look it up

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.320
but could you speak french for example

00:01:38.079 --> 00:01:42.159
if you were always looking it up on

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.560
google translate

00:01:42.159 --> 00:01:47.360
could you take derivatives in math if

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:49.360
you always had to look up how to do it

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:52.159
no of course not

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:55.040
you need key aspects of whatever you're

00:01:52.159 --> 00:01:57.600
learning in long-term memory for you to

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:58.560
be able to truly have learned anything

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:01.360
new

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:02.960
and for you to gain expertise in any

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.960
topic

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:09.599
now learning often involves practice

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:11.760
practice is what helps strengthen those

00:02:09.599 --> 00:02:13.840
neural connections as you can see

00:02:11.760 --> 00:02:15.360
metaphorically here

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:18.239
so ultimately

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:19.120
those sets of links become sort of like

00:02:18.239 --> 00:02:22.319
this

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:24.720
big thick nice necklace that you can

00:02:22.319 --> 00:02:26.800
easily pull into mind whenever you've

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:29.360
learned something

00:02:26.800 --> 00:02:31.680
so this brings me to an important aspect

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:32.800
of learning that sometimes people aren't

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:34.319
aware of

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:37.760
and that is

00:02:34.319 --> 00:02:40.319
what is the most important and powerful

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:42.879
technique that people can use to learn

00:02:40.319 --> 00:02:45.120
most efficiently

00:02:42.879 --> 00:02:47.440
i'm going to present four different

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:48.959
approaches here that are commonly used

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:51.519
for learning

00:02:48.959 --> 00:02:53.840
what i'd like you to do is just think

00:02:51.519 --> 00:02:56.319
which of these four approaches that i'm

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:58.720
going to present here is the approach

00:02:56.319 --> 00:03:00.720
that you use most often for your

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:04.080
learning the first technique i'll

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:05.920
mention is that of rereading

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:07.840
rereading would make sense as a

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:11.040
potentially powerful technique for

00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:14.080
learning because it involves repetition

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:16.080
then there's highlighting or underline

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:19.840
which involves motor neurons as you're

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:22.560
drawing and perhaps thus reinforcing

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:25.120
whatever is on the page

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:28.080
or it could be retrieval practice or

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:29.840
recall for example using a flashcard to

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:31.680
check and see whether you know the

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:34.879
information

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:38.080
or it could be creating what's called a

00:03:34.879 --> 00:03:40.640
concept map such as the one i show here

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:42.480
where you write down key concepts of

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:45.840
what you're learning and then see how

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:47.920
they integrate together

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:50.319
hopefully of these techniques you see

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:52.000
here you have in mind which one you

00:03:50.319 --> 00:03:53.599
think is best

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.879
which one is it

00:03:53.599 --> 00:03:58.319
well as it turns out it's retrieval

00:03:56.879 --> 00:04:01.120
practice

00:03:58.319 --> 00:04:03.120
and indeed hundreds of studies have

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:05.439
shown that retrieval practice is the

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:06.720
most effective technique for helping

00:04:05.439 --> 00:04:08.480
students learn

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:10.480
not only because it helps students

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:12.640
remember the material

00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:16.160
but because it actually helps build a

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:17.600
better understanding of the material

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:18.639
why

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:21.040
well

00:04:18.639 --> 00:04:24.000
when a student is first learning

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.880
something there are these weak links as

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:29.520
you see here being created in long-term

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:32.880
memory in the neocortex

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:35.600
but it is when you retrieve that memory

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:37.360
over and over over time

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:40.479
those sets of links

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:44.639
those are what help build the strong

00:04:40.479 --> 00:04:47.040
links in the neocortex of memory

00:04:44.639 --> 00:04:49.520
why does retrieval practice also help

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.800
with understanding

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:56.000
well in some sense it's because you're

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:59.919
not only learning what something is

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:02.400
you're also learning what it is not

00:04:59.919 --> 00:05:04.800
now of course some students need more

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:07.680
retrieval practice with the material to

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:10.400
learn effectively it all depends on a

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:12.080
student's pre-existing knowledge base

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:14.880
their motivation

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:17.919
and their innate neural underpinnings

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:19.919
all of which can differ substantially

00:05:17.919 --> 00:05:21.840
but even though it can take some

00:05:19.919 --> 00:05:25.039
students longer to learn

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:27.199
those slower students like me

00:05:25.039 --> 00:05:29.520
can learn the material just as well and

00:05:27.199 --> 00:05:31.520
sometimes even better than faster

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:33.280
students

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:36.000
but what happens

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:38.320
if for example a student is very very

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
busy with all sorts of other activities

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:42.080
and they just don't get around to

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.919
retrieving and practicing with what

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:47.600
they've learned

00:05:43.919 --> 00:05:50.080
well in that case they're not using

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:53.280
those particular dendritic spines that

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:56.240
they used for the learning and so

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:59.280
their little synaptic genit

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:01.600
sweep those connections away

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:03.600
we can actually see this process going

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:05.319
on in real life

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:08.080
you're all budding

00:06:05.319 --> 00:06:09.919
neuroscientists now so you can recognize

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:11.440
this as

00:06:09.919 --> 00:06:14.639
the leg

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:17.759
of a neuron the dendrite

00:06:14.639 --> 00:06:20.560
it's a light microscopy image and this

00:06:17.759 --> 00:06:23.120
image was taken before learning and

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:25.759
before sleep you see all these little

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:27.919
toes the dendritic spines that are

00:06:25.759 --> 00:06:28.880
dangling off of it

00:06:27.919 --> 00:06:30.400
now

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:32.080
can you imagine

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:35.360
what would this

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:36.639
particular living neuron or living

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:37.919
dendrite

00:06:36.639 --> 00:06:41.520
look like

00:06:37.919 --> 00:06:43.680
after learning and after sleep

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:46.400
we can actually see it

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:49.120
here's an image of the same living

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:50.240
neuron after learning and after sleep

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:51.680
look here

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:52.639
you can see

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:55.199
this is

00:06:52.639 --> 00:06:59.120
the this lower image

00:06:55.199 --> 00:07:02.240
has a new dendritic spine that's emerged

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:05.199
where there was none before

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:07.520
so it's actually during sleep that

00:07:05.199 --> 00:07:08.960
neural connections are really formed and

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:10.479
strengthened

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:12.800
this is why it's a good idea for

00:07:10.479 --> 00:07:15.039
students of course after they've learned

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:18.000
the material during the day

00:07:15.039 --> 00:07:20.240
to set aside maybe two to five minutes

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.639
right before they go to sleep to remind

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:24.960
themselves of what they really want to

00:07:22.639 --> 00:07:27.759
learn or remember

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:31.360
that will help their neurons to know in

00:07:27.759 --> 00:07:32.639
some sense the ideas concepts or

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:35.280
techniques

00:07:32.639 --> 00:07:38.880
that are important to be practicing

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:41.680
during sleep indeed during sleep

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:44.319
those connections are used hundreds of

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:46.000
times as the brain practices with those

00:07:44.319 --> 00:07:48.160
thoughts and activities during the

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.440
sleeping process

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:55.360
so this can be why it's so important to

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:57.280
space out learning over a number of days

00:07:55.360 --> 00:08:00.000
let's say a student has

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.680
say five hours for learning involving a

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.479
given topic

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:05.440
they may wish to break that up into one

00:08:04.479 --> 00:08:07.759
hour

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:09.280
per day for five days

00:08:07.759 --> 00:08:12.639
rather than

00:08:09.280 --> 00:08:15.120
five hours all crammed in one day

00:08:12.639 --> 00:08:17.840
this one day of cramming

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:20.080
means that the connections are actually

00:08:17.840 --> 00:08:23.520
weaker and their little synaptic janitor

00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:27.440
can more easily sweep them away

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:30.479
whereas for this spaced repetition in

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:31.840
learning one hour each day over these

00:08:30.479 --> 00:08:33.760
five days

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:37.680
you not only learn

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:40.399
but you also practice during sleep

00:08:37.680 --> 00:08:43.039
so in some sense you're getting twice

00:08:40.399 --> 00:08:45.920
the bang for the buck for your effort

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:47.519
with spaced out learning as opposed to

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:50.000
cramming

00:08:47.519 --> 00:08:52.880
metaphorically speaking since i

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.120
absolutely love metaphors

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:56.880
you can think of it as a little bit like

00:08:55.120 --> 00:08:59.120
a brick wall

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:02.240
you lay a layer of bricks and then

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:03.920
mortar bricks and mortar but before you

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:07.279
go too high

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:10.320
you let that layer of bricks

00:09:07.279 --> 00:09:11.200
dry the mortar to dry

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:13.440
and

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:14.480
if you take your time with learning like

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.360
this

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:19.920
it'll create a very good foundation

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:22.240
if you don't however you're going to get

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:23.760
a structure for learning that looks more

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:27.279
like this

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:29.680
very poor foundation for learning

00:09:27.279 --> 00:09:32.320
this is also irreverently sometimes

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:33.519
referred to as the meathead theory of

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:36.880
learning

00:09:33.519 --> 00:09:39.600
as it turns out both muscular tissue and

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:41.680
neural tissue are excitable tissues

00:09:39.600 --> 00:09:43.600
so just as it takes time to build

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:45.600
muscular structure

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:47.519
it takes time to build

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:50.320
neural structure

00:09:47.519 --> 00:09:52.959
of course however some students can

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:54.640
learn much more quickly while others

00:09:52.959 --> 00:09:57.279
much more slowly

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:58.959
just as there are natural athletes

00:09:57.279 --> 00:10:02.240
compared to

00:09:58.959 --> 00:10:05.680
natural klutz's like me

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:08.000
now to another aspect of learning

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:11.120
this relates to what is called working

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.800
memory which involves the limited set of

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:16.000
ideas or thoughts that we can

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:18.320
temporarily hold in mind and work with

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:21.760
so for example if i gave you the numbers

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:24.240
seven four three and two for you to

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:27.519
remember you would hold them in working

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:28.720
memory by repeating them seven four

00:10:27.519 --> 00:10:31.120
three two

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:32.640
but if you stopped repeating you'd

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:34.560
forget

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:37.680
long-term memory on the other hand can

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:40.000
hold information for a long time but it

00:10:37.680 --> 00:10:42.720
can take much more effort to get

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.680
information out of working memory and

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:47.040
into

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:49.760
long-term memory as sets up links that

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:52.000
form those memories

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:54.800
i like to think of working memory as

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.519
kind of like an octopus sometimes i call

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:59.279
it the attentional octopus

00:10:57.519 --> 00:11:02.079
well maybe you'd be better off calling

00:10:59.279 --> 00:11:04.640
it a quadrupos because instead of having

00:11:02.079 --> 00:11:08.240
eight arms to hold information

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:11.120
your working memory has on average only

00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:13.360
about four arms

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:14.959
long-term memory on the other hand is

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:17.600
quite different

00:11:14.959 --> 00:11:19.680
it's more like a locker

00:11:17.600 --> 00:11:24.240
and within that locker

00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:26.320
is stored all your sets of neural links

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:28.560
you can think of it like this

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:32.000
your working memory

00:11:28.560 --> 00:11:34.079
works hard to create sets of links in

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.600
long-term memory about whatever you're

00:11:34.079 --> 00:11:38.160
learning

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:40.640
once working memory has created those

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:41.760
sets of links and set them in long-term

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.000
memory

00:11:41.760 --> 00:11:47.680
it can then be easy for your working

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.600
memory to reach out and grab those sets

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:50.480
of links

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:52.320
so

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:55.600
this brings me

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:58.639
to my younger daughter rachel

00:11:55.600 --> 00:12:01.040
now not before this little video snippet

00:11:58.639 --> 00:12:04.800
was filmed that you're going to see

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:07.200
rachel had learned how to back up a car

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:09.839
so i asked rachel if she might model for

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:12.320
us on video what it felt like when she

00:12:09.839 --> 00:12:13.760
was first backing up a car

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:16.560
here she is

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:18.399
modeling what it felt like

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:20.000
watch her little face as she's trying to

00:12:18.399 --> 00:12:22.320
back up the car

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
notice how she's looking to the side she

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:26.639
looks up front she looks at us she's

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.880
looking behind her her working memory is

00:12:26.639 --> 00:12:31.760
overwhelmed she doesn't really know what

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:34.639
to do and then of course she ends up

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:37.440
heading off towards the ditch

00:12:34.639 --> 00:12:40.240
this gives us a sense of the process

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:42.639
that occurs as people are first learning

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.720
something especially if that something

00:12:42.639 --> 00:12:46.800
is rather complex

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:50.480
their working memory is trying to

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:52.560
integrate all this different information

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:55.040
so you can think of it as their working

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:57.920
memory has what's called a heavy

00:12:55.040 --> 00:13:01.360
cognitive load and that means that the

00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:03.040
arms of their attentional octopus

00:13:01.360 --> 00:13:05.040
are already full

00:13:03.040 --> 00:13:07.519
there's not room in their working memory

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:09.760
for any other information

00:13:07.519 --> 00:13:11.920
so if i was sitting beside rachel i

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:14.399
would not be asking her as she's

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:17.440
learning how to back up the car hey by

00:13:14.399 --> 00:13:19.440
the way what are you going to do today

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:22.160
if she also tried to put some

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:23.600
attentional octopus arms around what i

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:26.480
was saying

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:28.720
she could ultimately become completely

00:13:26.480 --> 00:13:31.839
overwhelmed and maybe even hit another

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:34.720
car as she was trying to back up

00:13:31.839 --> 00:13:35.680
but once rachel learned how to back up a

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:38.880
car

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:41.199
it became easy for her to do

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:42.800
all she had to do was think hey i want

00:13:41.199 --> 00:13:45.680
to back up the car

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:48.880
she can then pull that memory those sets

00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:50.000
of links of how to back up the car to

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:52.720
mind

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:55.600
she has a light cognitive load in other

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:58.720
words she's got attentional arms

00:13:55.600 --> 00:14:01.680
available for other thoughts like is my

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:03.279
seatbelt fastened or what's the song on

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:05.839
the radio

00:14:03.279 --> 00:14:07.040
so let's turn our attention now to a

00:14:05.839 --> 00:14:09.199
student

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:11.839
let's say that our student is

00:14:09.199 --> 00:14:14.079
sitting down to take an exam and they

00:14:11.839 --> 00:14:16.240
practice well for the exam

00:14:14.079 --> 00:14:18.160
so they sit down they take a look at the

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:19.279
first problem and they go hmm this is a

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:21.600
tough one

00:14:19.279 --> 00:14:24.000
but since they practiced they can

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:26.720
quickly see that certain sets of links

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.519
that they've already learned can easily

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:31.440
connect with other links and still other

00:14:29.519 --> 00:14:34.399
links and boom

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:36.320
suddenly they've solved the problem

00:14:34.399 --> 00:14:38.720
but on the other hand

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:40.480
if students haven't studied using

00:14:38.720 --> 00:14:43.040
retrieval practice

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:45.519
they can sit down to a test and what can

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:47.600
happen is surprise

00:14:45.519 --> 00:14:49.760
they realize that where they may have

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:52.240
thought they knew the material

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:54.160
in reality they didn't

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:56.560
in fact when they start to work on the

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:59.680
problem they realize there are no sets

00:14:56.560 --> 00:15:01.600
of links in long-term memory for them

00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:03.519
what they thought was in long-term

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:05.040
memory was actually only in their

00:15:03.519 --> 00:15:08.560
working memory

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:10.880
they didn't really know the material

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:13.519
what happens then is that these students

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:14.399
can come to us as teachers and say you

00:15:13.519 --> 00:15:17.519
know

00:15:14.399 --> 00:15:21.199
i suffer from test anxiety

00:15:17.519 --> 00:15:23.760
but it often isn't test anxiety at all

00:15:21.199 --> 00:15:26.720
it's the fact that they have not learned

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:29.040
the material well they haven't practiced

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:30.399
and place sets of links in long-term

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:32.079
memory

00:15:30.399 --> 00:15:34.160
probably the biggest part of the

00:15:32.079 --> 00:15:36.240
challenge for our students is that we've

00:15:34.160 --> 00:15:37.680
never taught them how to study

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:40.079
effectively

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:42.959
they think their lack of ability is due

00:15:40.079 --> 00:15:44.639
to their stress when it actually relates

00:15:42.959 --> 00:15:46.800
to the fact that they haven't learned

00:15:44.639 --> 00:15:48.800
the material properly

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:50.639
and we can make things worse for our

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:52.079
students when we send them off to

00:15:50.639 --> 00:15:54.800
counseling

00:15:52.079 --> 00:15:56.959
which also allows them to procrastinate

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:58.320
which is another frequent problem for

00:15:56.959 --> 00:16:01.279
students

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:04.000
all this instead of teaching them how to

00:16:01.279 --> 00:16:07.279
effectively learn the material

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:09.600
the reality is the common facet of

00:16:07.279 --> 00:16:12.160
experts of all kinds

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:14.639
is that they have lots and lots of

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:16.959
well-practiced sets of links in

00:16:14.639 --> 00:16:19.839
long-term memory

00:16:16.959 --> 00:16:22.880
now an important idea for teachers is

00:16:19.839 --> 00:16:24.399
that working memory capacities

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:26.639
can vary

00:16:24.399 --> 00:16:28.720
so as i've mentioned a typical working

00:16:26.639 --> 00:16:32.240
memory can hold about four pieces of

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:35.680
information or chunks of information

00:16:32.240 --> 00:16:37.680
a chunk can vary in size and content

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:40.720
it's something you know so well you can

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:43.279
easily pull it to mind as a single unit

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:45.920
whether it's for example a section of a

00:16:43.279 --> 00:16:48.480
song you can play well on the piano or

00:16:45.920 --> 00:16:51.360
an equation you know how to work with or

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:53.680
a sentence in a foreign language

00:16:51.360 --> 00:16:55.199
some people have a lesser capacity

00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:58.000
working memory

00:16:55.199 --> 00:17:00.399
for example i've got a lesser capacity

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:03.519
working memory i'm lucky to be able to

00:17:00.399 --> 00:17:05.839
hold maybe three pieces of information

00:17:03.519 --> 00:17:08.640
in mind at once but of course some

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:10.720
people have a greater capacity working

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:12.160
memory than just four pieces of

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:14.640
information

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:16.959
my colleague in teaching the popular

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:18.400
course we both teach on coursera

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:21.120
learning how to learn

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:23.760
is terry sinowski the francis crick

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:26.160
professor at the salk institute

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:28.720
terry is one of only 12 living human

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:31.120
beings who is simultaneously a member of

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:33.840
the national academy of sciences of

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:37.039
engineering and of medicine

00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:39.120
terry has an enormously large working

00:17:37.039 --> 00:17:40.880
memory capacity

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:43.039
the difference between us

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:46.880
is that although i can learn what terry

00:17:43.039 --> 00:17:48.000
learns i am generally much slower than

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:50.160
he is

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.799
unless of course it's something i have a

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:54.480
lot of experience with by comparison to

00:17:52.799 --> 00:17:57.280
terry

00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:59.280
you might think well yes but what about

00:17:57.280 --> 00:18:01.840
growth mindset

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:05.520
maybe we just haven't improved our

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:07.760
working memory capacity yet

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:09.760
of course having the right attitude

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:12.320
about what we're learning can make an

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:15.039
enormous difference it certainly did for

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:17.600
me what i decided to change my mind back

00:18:15.039 --> 00:18:20.320
in my mid-20s about whether or not i

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:23.039
could learn in math and science

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:26.480
but we have to be realistic about what

00:18:23.039 --> 00:18:28.960
growth mindset actually applies to

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:30.480
i mean if we have two kids with

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:33.039
different heights

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:36.000
growth mindset is not going to make a

00:18:33.039 --> 00:18:38.559
big difference in whether or not one kid

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:41.760
can become taller

00:18:38.559 --> 00:18:43.919
it's it's a physical characteristic

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:46.320
working memory capacity is also a

00:18:43.919 --> 00:18:48.480
physical characteristic and it's one

00:18:46.320 --> 00:18:51.280
that a student can't really change no

00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:53.200
matter how hard they try

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:54.400
so let's look

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:57.120
at how

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:59.600
working memory capacity changes as

00:18:57.120 --> 00:19:00.720
students mature when a child is very

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:02.320
young

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:04.720
it turns out their working memory

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:07.120
capacity no surprise

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:09.039
is very small

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:12.240
they can forget what you tell them is

00:19:09.039 --> 00:19:13.840
pretty much as fast as you can tell them

00:19:12.240 --> 00:19:15.360
but as children

00:19:13.840 --> 00:19:17.919
mature

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:20.880
their working memory capacity gets

00:19:17.919 --> 00:19:22.640
larger until by the time they're about

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:25.679
15 years old

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:28.400
they can hold on average well anywhere

00:19:25.679 --> 00:19:32.559
between maybe three pieces

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:34.400
to five pieces of information in mind at

00:19:32.559 --> 00:19:37.200
once

00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:39.360
this means that a typical teacher is

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:42.480
going to have a wide range of working

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:44.320
memory capacities and learning speeds in

00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:47.520
their classroom

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:50.280
this is handled today by a technique

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:53.360
known as differentiation

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:54.799
differentiation involves scaffolding

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:57.760
information

00:19:54.799 --> 00:19:59.840
that is breaking information up into

00:19:57.760 --> 00:20:02.799
smaller chunks

00:19:59.840 --> 00:20:05.600
scaffolding allows students who grasp

00:20:02.799 --> 00:20:07.200
the material more slowly to still learn

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:09.520
the material

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:12.000
slower learners also benefit very

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:14.000
greatly from more practice with the

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.559
material

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.320
of course this

00:20:15.559 --> 00:20:20.320
step-by-step approach with much more

00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:23.520
practice for those with lesser capacity

00:20:20.320 --> 00:20:25.679
working memory can take much more time

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:27.440
but what do we do in the classroom when

00:20:25.679 --> 00:20:30.480
we have someone

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:32.960
like for example this who has a

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:34.720
prodigiously large working memory

00:20:32.960 --> 00:20:37.039
capacity

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:39.679
a student with such working memory

00:20:37.039 --> 00:20:41.840
capacity can move out of the realm of

00:20:39.679 --> 00:20:43.919
what a typical teacher can handle when

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:46.960
they're trying to differentiate and help

00:20:43.919 --> 00:20:49.440
all the students in their classrooms

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:51.679
thus my colleague terry sinowski was

00:20:49.440 --> 00:20:54.400
seen as a troublemaker in his high

00:20:51.679 --> 00:20:56.720
school because he asked a myriad of

00:20:54.400 --> 00:21:00.400
questions that his teachers were often

00:20:56.720 --> 00:21:03.440
simply unable to answer

00:21:00.400 --> 00:21:08.159
this brings me to an important topic

00:21:03.440 --> 00:21:10.080
called the expertise reversal effect

00:21:08.159 --> 00:21:12.799
it turns out that the more knowledgeable

00:21:10.080 --> 00:21:16.799
a student is about a topic

00:21:12.799 --> 00:21:19.600
the less guidance they can need too much

00:21:16.799 --> 00:21:22.159
guidance in these situations actually

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:24.400
impedes their learning

00:21:22.159 --> 00:21:26.000
think about how frustrated students can

00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:28.720
get if they

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:31.039
knew as much or even far more than their

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:32.159
teacher on a topic and yet we held them

00:21:31.039 --> 00:21:35.120
back

00:21:32.159 --> 00:21:37.679
instead of recognizing and honoring

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:40.480
neurodiversity in other words we can

00:21:37.679 --> 00:21:44.000
simply stick everyone in the same slot

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:46.080
and say they must learn identically

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:48.799
instead of allowing students like terry

00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:50.960
to flourish we can frustrate these

00:21:48.799 --> 00:21:54.240
gifted students to such an extent that

00:21:50.960 --> 00:21:56.840
the allure of drugs or anything besides

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:59.760
school can become

00:21:56.840 --> 00:22:02.000
overwhelming our school systems need to

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:04.480
accommodate our gifted students like

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.200
terry as well as those who benefit from

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:08.559
slower learning with far more practice

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:10.559
like me

00:22:08.559 --> 00:22:12.559
that's an important part of the

00:22:10.559 --> 00:22:15.679
educational process

00:22:12.559 --> 00:22:17.919
not only to reach those within typical

00:22:15.679 --> 00:22:18.880
standard deviations of how brains

00:22:17.919 --> 00:22:22.000
function

00:22:18.880 --> 00:22:23.360
but even those who fall far outside the

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.440
mean

00:22:23.360 --> 00:22:27.679
incidentally if you're looking for the

00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:28.559
research citations involved in this

00:22:27.679 --> 00:22:32.559
topic

00:22:28.559 --> 00:22:36.400
feel free to go to this url

