if they know how to do the geometric

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:04.400
distribution

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:06.319
and how to do the binomial distribution

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:08.960
but they don't know

00:40:06.319 --> 00:40:11.599
when to use one approach versus the

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:14.480
other off they can go on a final

00:40:11.599 --> 00:40:17.200
examination correctly using

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:19.920
the wrong technique unfortunately

00:40:17.200 --> 00:40:22.319
textbooks often supply their problems

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:24.720
using a blocked approach

00:40:22.319 --> 00:40:27.359
whereas students actually learn much

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:30.160
better using interleaving

00:40:27.359 --> 00:40:31.119
so a good teaching approach is to try to

00:40:30.160 --> 00:40:33.599
ensure

00:40:31.119 --> 00:40:35.680
that despite the way that material is

00:40:33.599 --> 00:40:37.839
presented in textbooks

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:40.160
that students are presented with

00:40:37.839 --> 00:40:42.079
interleaved problem sets in whatever

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:44.880
they're learning

00:40:42.079 --> 00:40:46.880
it's important to remember that when you

00:40:44.880 --> 00:40:49.760
eliminate seeming

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:51.760
rote approaches to learning disparaging

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:55.040
these type of approaches by using

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:59.280
phrases such as drill and kill

00:40:55.040 --> 00:41:02.079
you are actually eliminating the easiest

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:03.920
best way the brain has to handle routine

00:41:02.079 --> 00:41:05.599
learning tasks

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:07.680
instead

00:41:05.599 --> 00:41:11.839
it's best to think of procedural

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:14.160
learning as drill to skill i'd like to

00:41:11.839 --> 00:41:16.400
turn now briefly to touch on a topic

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:19.520
that may seem to have little to do with

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:21.040
how the brain works and how it learns

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:23.839
but what i'm going to talk about

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:26.480
involves such a common and commonly

00:41:23.839 --> 00:41:29.040
misapplied approach to teaching that i

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:31.119
think it's important to talk about it

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:35.680
and that relates to the problem of

00:41:31.119 --> 00:41:36.720
collaborative and team learning

00:41:35.680 --> 00:41:38.400
so

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:40.560
veronica mintz

00:41:38.400 --> 00:41:42.400
is a high school student or was a high

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:45.280
school student who wrote an op-ed in the

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:46.400
new york times that describes the common

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:50.000
challenges

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:52.079
students incur in today's teaching

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:53.920
she estimates that

00:41:52.079 --> 00:41:57.119
80 percent of her learning at school

00:41:53.920 --> 00:41:59.920
took place in collaborative teams

00:41:57.119 --> 00:42:02.240
the consequence was that she grew to

00:41:59.920 --> 00:42:05.760
dread school because of her teacher's

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:08.000
inability to manage students

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:10.079
responsibility for controlling student

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.839
behavior was being foisted off on

00:42:10.079 --> 00:42:14.480
students who had little ability or

00:42:11.839 --> 00:42:17.040
training to deal with the complex issues

00:42:14.480 --> 00:42:20.640
involved in motivating their peers who

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:22.880
often had no interest in learning

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:26.560
at the heart of the problem of group

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:29.760
learning in school in fact is the idea

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:32.000
that group learning is a panacea that

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:33.440
generally allows for excitement

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:35.520
engagement

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:37.520
and creativity

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:39.760
oh contraire

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:41.359
let me give you an example

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:43.599
when i was going through engineering

00:42:41.359 --> 00:42:46.079
school i was on a team that was tasked

00:42:43.599 --> 00:42:47.599
with designing a high efficiency heat

00:42:46.079 --> 00:42:50.240
exchanger

00:42:47.599 --> 00:42:53.040
the three guys on my team poo-pooed my

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:55.839
idea instead devising ideas that it

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:58.480
turned out were virtually identical to

00:42:55.839 --> 00:43:00.800
the other ideas in the class

00:42:58.480 --> 00:43:04.000
so when the professor happened to stop

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:06.000
by i mentioned my idea

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:08.000
he said

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:10.720
that's very interesting and hasn't been

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:14.480
done before you should try it

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:16.640
grudgingly my team tried the idea

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:18.800
our heat exchanger turned out to have

00:43:16.640 --> 00:43:22.319
the highest efficiency

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:24.800
heat exchanger of any exchanger that had

00:43:22.319 --> 00:43:27.680
been designed in the 20 years that the

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:30.880
professor had been teaching that class

00:43:27.680 --> 00:43:33.839
i'm not saying this to blow my own horn

00:43:30.880 --> 00:43:35.520
i'm saying this because in fact

00:43:33.839 --> 00:43:38.000
research has shown

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:41.040
that it is individuals rather than

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:43.040
groups who are by far the most creative

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:45.680
when it comes to scientific or

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:48.800
technological breakthroughs

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:50.960
one massive review of tens of millions

00:43:48.800 --> 00:43:52.480
of patents and papers found that it was

00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:54.400
one person

00:43:52.480 --> 00:43:56.800
perhaps two or

00:43:54.400 --> 00:43:59.599
at most three individuals working

00:43:56.800 --> 00:44:01.200
together who made truly creative

00:43:59.599 --> 00:44:03.599
breakthroughs

00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:04.800
larger groups could accomplish large

00:44:03.599 --> 00:44:07.760
tasks

00:44:04.800 --> 00:44:09.520
but not truly creative tasks

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:11.760
so if you're planning to have your

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:14.640
students work collaboratively

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:17.040
keep in mind that collaboration is not a

00:44:14.640 --> 00:44:22.000
cure-all for creative work

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:24.000
in fact too much can diminish creativity

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:25.920
but there's more

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:27.119
there's the biggest challenge in all of

00:44:25.920 --> 00:44:28.319
teamwork

00:44:27.119 --> 00:44:30.640
and that is

00:44:28.319 --> 00:44:34.079
that there will always be some team

00:44:30.640 --> 00:44:37.119
members who do not pull their weight

00:44:34.079 --> 00:44:39.680
to understand this we should step back

00:44:37.119 --> 00:44:43.280
and look at an article in the chronicle

00:44:39.680 --> 00:44:45.280
of higher education by harvard professor

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:47.680
robert coles

00:44:45.280 --> 00:44:50.079
coles told the story of a young student

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:52.960
who was working her way through harvard

00:44:50.079 --> 00:44:56.800
by cleaning dorm rooms

00:44:52.960 --> 00:45:00.000
one student let's call him michael

00:44:56.800 --> 00:45:02.160
was a pre-med student who was already a

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:04.560
successful journalist

00:45:02.160 --> 00:45:07.119
michael would rudely and crudely

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:09.200
proposition this young woman whenever

00:45:07.119 --> 00:45:12.480
she cleaned his room

00:45:09.200 --> 00:45:16.160
what was worse was that both she

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:19.680
and this student had taken classes in

00:45:16.160 --> 00:45:22.319
morality and ethics together and michael

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:25.280
apparently had excelled

00:45:22.319 --> 00:45:27.920
so here was this star student a seeming

00:45:25.280 --> 00:45:30.160
paragon of society at harvard

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:32.800
and the reality was that he learned

00:45:30.160 --> 00:45:36.480
nothing in his ethics and morality

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:40.079
classes despite his top grades

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:43.599
in fact as this young woman pointed out

00:45:40.079 --> 00:45:47.200
worldwide there are many philosophers

00:45:43.599 --> 00:45:49.839
scientists poets and politicians who

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:52.319
have experienced plenty of morality

00:45:49.839 --> 00:45:55.280
training through their early lives

00:45:52.319 --> 00:45:58.240
and have gone on to support despicable

00:45:55.280 --> 00:46:00.880
causes and regimes

00:45:58.240 --> 00:46:04.240
in the end this woman resigned from what

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:06.640
she called fancy phony cambridge

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:10.160
with her departure harvard lost a

00:46:06.640 --> 00:46:11.440
guiding light in morality while instead

00:46:10.160 --> 00:46:14.240
with michael

00:46:11.440 --> 00:46:16.160
graduating and ethically repulsive

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:18.240
character

00:46:16.160 --> 00:46:21.040
it's important to remember

00:46:18.240 --> 00:46:24.079
that there will always be a few students

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:25.599
like michael amongst us and amongst our

00:46:24.079 --> 00:46:28.000
teams

00:46:25.599 --> 00:46:31.280
such students will parry back the line

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:34.560
of morality even as they can take deep

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:37.599
advantage of those they're working with

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:40.240
to deal with these kinds of situations

00:46:37.599 --> 00:46:43.520
and also with situations where students

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:47.280
may be overworked overwhelmed and still

00:46:43.520 --> 00:46:50.160
willing to take advantage if necessary

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:52.400
you might give students the tools that

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:55.520
they need through life

00:46:52.400 --> 00:46:58.240
through using a case study

00:46:55.520 --> 00:47:00.800
here's a good example case study that

00:46:58.240 --> 00:47:04.000
may be of help this is how to manage

00:47:00.800 --> 00:47:06.960
yourself on a collaborative team

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:09.359
this brief essay describes a typical

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:11.920
student who takes advantage of others

00:47:09.359 --> 00:47:14.400
and tell students what to do

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:16.880
if they find themselves in a team with

00:47:14.400 --> 00:47:19.680
this kind of situation

00:47:16.880 --> 00:47:20.800
this form as well as the others i'll be

00:47:19.680 --> 00:47:23.440
mentioning

00:47:20.800 --> 00:47:26.480
can be found with research citations

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:28.559
that i point out earlier

00:47:26.480 --> 00:47:31.119
social emotional learning is

00:47:28.559 --> 00:47:33.280
exceptionally important

00:47:31.119 --> 00:47:35.920
talking through a case study like this

00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:38.240
one allows students to understand one of

00:47:35.920 --> 00:47:40.079
the most important aspects of social

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:42.880
emotional learning

00:47:40.079 --> 00:47:46.319
one that is typically neglected and that

00:47:42.880 --> 00:47:47.920
is the importance of saying no when

00:47:46.319 --> 00:47:50.000
necessary

00:47:47.920 --> 00:47:52.559
learning to put up boundaries is

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:55.119
exceptionally important especially for

00:47:52.559 --> 00:47:57.920
young girls who are often socialized to

00:47:55.119 --> 00:48:00.240
be empathetic and agreeable

00:47:57.920 --> 00:48:03.119
think about it if you always teach that

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:06.960
empathy is extraordinarily important

00:48:03.119 --> 00:48:08.400
who's going to listen to and heed this

00:48:06.960 --> 00:48:09.280
message

00:48:08.400 --> 00:48:12.559
well

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:16.720
it's those who are already empathetic in

00:48:12.559 --> 00:48:19.119
fact by over emphasis on empathy without

00:48:16.720 --> 00:48:21.119
committing training on how to say no and

00:48:19.119 --> 00:48:22.880
set limits in the behavior that we

00:48:21.119 --> 00:48:24.800
accept from others

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:28.480
we can set students

00:48:24.800 --> 00:48:30.960
especially kind and empathetic students

00:48:28.480 --> 00:48:33.440
up for codependency

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:34.960
that is the situation where a person can

00:48:33.440 --> 00:48:37.520
put up with almost any kind of

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:40.000
mistreatment because they think they're

00:48:37.520 --> 00:48:42.160
helping others

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:46.079
there are other ways beyond the case

00:48:42.160 --> 00:48:48.240
study that teachers can use forms and

00:48:46.079 --> 00:48:50.319
checklists to help them better manage

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:52.720
teams in their classroom

